Should\nI be setting up multiple open claws?\nShould I be setting up separate sub\naents? What's the best model? There's so\nmany advantages to sub aents. My setup\nis kind of complex. I have open claws. I\nhave sub aents. I'm keeping this\nbeginner friendly for now, but right now\nsub aents are a big advantage because\none parallel work your open claw can\nspin up to five sub aents at a time. So\nthat's five sub aents that could be\ndoing work at the same time. So it's\ngetting work done faster. You're saving\nmoney because you can use again the\nright models for the right tasks. Each\none of these sub aents get their own\ncontext window. So if you have your main\nopen claw doing everything, it can get\nconfused and slow down because it's\nhaving context in its context window\nabout every task it's doing. Sub agents\nkeep the context windows clean. Failure\nprotection. So if any of the sub aents\never crash, your orchestrator agent can\njust figure out what's going on and fix\nit. If your main orchestrator agent ever\ncrashed because you have it doing 20\nthings at once, everything's toast. So,\nit's good insurance to be using sub\nagents. And then auto archive. So, when\nagents are done, when sub agents are\ndone, they can just get shut down and\ncleaned up so things keep moving\nsmoother. So, that's why we're setting\nup sub agents here and not multiple open\nclaws. So, we got our first sub agent\nset up. They're doing some coding work\nfor us. Next, let's add some things to\nour mission control that make this all a\nlot more organized. If you haven't set\nup a mission control yet, I'll put a\nvideo down below for setting up a\nmission control. I just filmed it last\nweek in Japan about how to get this set\nup. You should definitely see that if\nyou haven't yet, you can watch that\nright after this. But I want to show you\na few things you can set up to be better\norganized here. Number one is this team\nscreen. This is an org structure. I like\nsetting this up once you're spinning up\nsub aents because this does a couple of\nthings. One, it keeps you organized, so\nyou know which sub aents are in charge\nof what, but two, it also keeps your\norchestrator agent organized. Henry, at\nany point when it needs to do work, can\ncome in here and check to see which sub\nagent it needs to give work to. Henry's\nthe boss. I don't tell it which sub\naents to use. It figures it out on its\nown. And because I have this team\nscreen, it can figure out on its own\nwhich sub agents it needs to give work\nto. So, what you're going to want to do\nis you're going to want to go to your\nmain orchestrator agent and you're going\nto want to say to it, I want a screen in\nour mission control that shows our\nentire team structure, showing each sub\nagent, each agent, what model they're\nworking on, and what their\nresponsibilities are. This will keep you\nsuper organized, and you'll be able to\ncheck at any time like this as you scale\nup. It's a lot easier to scale up and\nadd more sub agents when you have a\nclear picture of what these agents are.\nIn a second, I'll go through setting up\na third sub agent, fourth sub agent, and\nshow you how to give them tasks that are\nreally, really helpful. But I want to\nshow you a couple more screens here. And\nreal quick before we do that, every\nFriday, by the way, I run a live boot\ncamp in the Vibe Coding Academy. I go\nthrough my mission control. I go through\nmy sub agents. So, you have any\nquestions for me, feel free to join the\nVibe Coding Academy down below and you\ncan join the live sessions and ask me\nquestions live. They're a lot of fun. A\nlot of people enjoy. There's over like a\nthousand people in there now. But\nanyway, back to this. This is the\ncalendar view. This is an important\nscreen to set up as well. This will\nallow you to track every scheduled task\nyour sub agents are doing. So, one of\nthe great things you can do with your\nsub agents, again, I'll show you how to\ndo it in a second, is schedule task with\nthem, right? So, I have different things\non here. I have a sub agent that looks\nat trends every day at noon, see what's\ntrending on X, on YouTube. I have sub\nagents that write me morning briefs. I\nhave sub agents that write me scripts\nfor YouTube videos. And I can come in\nhere in this calendar screen and see\nevery task that is scheduled, every\ncrown job that's scheduled by every sub\naent. So you want to set up a calendar\nscreen. Again, very, very simple. You go\nto your open call, say, \"Hey, I want a\ncalendar screen in my mission control.\nPlease build that out that shows all the\nscheduled tasks and crown jobs all our\nagents and sub aents have.\" You hit\nenter on that. Boom. You're good to go.\nYou get something that looks like this.\nIf you want, by the way, you can pause\nat any time, screenshot this, and\nactually give it to your OpenClaw and\nsay, \"Hey buddy, build this.\" And it\nwill spin up your new coding sub agent\nto build this out. So, if you think\nthese look good, I spent a lot of time\nmaking sure these look good. Feel free\nto screenshot it, send it to your OpenCL\nagent. And lastly, this is my favorite\nscreen. There's not much utility to this\nscreen, but it is a lot of fun. And hey,\nyou're allowed to have fun when using\nAI, and this is the office view. This\nallows me to see each agent working,\neach agent walking around doing\ndifferent tasks for me in real time.\nIt's a good way. I just have this up as\nI'm working during the day and I can\npeek over, oh what are my agents doing?\nWhat's Ralph doing? What's Codex doing?\nAnd I can see that all happening here.\nSo, you should also be building out an\noffice screen like this. It's just fun\nand you're allowed to have fun. Feel\nfree to screenshot this. Give it to your\nopen client. Say, \"Hey, can you build me\na 2D pixel art view of all my agents\nworking? I'd love to track my agents\ndoing work.\" give this to them and\nyou'll have this really cool screen set\nup. So, you got your coding agent set\nup. Let's set up a couple more that\nwould be helpful for you here and then\nI'll show you how to get really custom\nand figure out other agents you need.\nBut, let's talk about a researcher.\nLet's set up a researcher sub agent.\nOdds are you care about something going\non in the world that's current. If\nyou're watching this video, if you watch\nmy channel, you probably care about AI\nand current AI news and trends. So, you\nshould set up a researcher agent.\nEveryone should have one. This\nresearcher agent for me goes out every\nmorning and finds what's trending in\nopenclaw and vibe coding. So, here's\nwhat I like to do. I want to build a sub\nagent that you will use for all research\nactivities. Every morning at 8 a.m.,\nplease have the sub agent search the web\nto find trending news about AI and vibe\ncoding and AI agents. Also, please put\nthem in our AI agent org chart in\nmission control. Please use Quen 3.5 for\nthis sub agent or whatever model you\nwant to use. I think the cheap Chinese\nmodels are great for this activity, but\nit's up to you what you want to use. I\npersonally use a local model that's\nlocal on my computer running 24/7, so it\ncost me $0, but that's up to you. You\nhit enter on this, and now you'll have a\ntask scheduled every morning at 8 a.m.\nwhere your sub agent will go out and\nfind trending news for you. I like this\nbecause it helps me stay on top of what\nthe newest AI tools are so I can use\nthem, so I can show it to you guys. If\nyou want more helpful AI videos like\nthis, feel free to hit subscribe and\nturn on notifications down below. All I\ndo is make amazing AI videos. So again,\nthis is now going to set up a scheduled\nevent for your agent. Every morning at\n8:00 a.m., your agent is going to go in\nand they will be doing these tasks for\nyou. So, as you can see here, if my\ntrend radar is at noon, yours could be\nat 8 a.m. whenever you want. And now you\ncan look at your calendar screen and see\nexactly what your agents are up to and\nwhen they have tasks coming up. Now you\ncan start to see how this organization\nis coming together, right? We set up\nsome basic agents, right? If you set up\ntwo, you're good. You don't need to have\n20 like I do just now. You have them\ngoing, you see the results, and as they\ngo, you think of more use cases you can\nhave them do. And you slowly layer on on\ntop that. You don't want to do a\nthousand at once. I hate these videos\nwhere the creator goes, \"Oh, you got to\nset up this army of 50 different sub\naents. here's a GitHub repo of 50\ndifferent sub aents that will do work\nfor you and like no that is I think that\nis the biggest mistake because it's\ngoing to overwhelm you. You're not going\nto know what the hell is going on and\nit's going to turn you off and cause you\nto use none of it. The best way to\napproach this is one agent at a time,\none sub agent, one coding sub agent. It\nbuilds you some things. Then you add on\none research agent. Then from there you\ncan start doing really interesting\nthings. You can have a thumbnail\ndesigner. It doesn't have to be a\nthumbnail designer. It could be just any\nsort of visual designer you want. This\ncould be powered by Nano Banana. And\nevery time you do something, maybe you\nfind a new story, maybe your content\ncreator, your researcher agent finds a\nnew story, it hands it off to your\nvisual designer and that creates a\nthumbnail for something or a visual for\nsomething, right? We start to slowly add\nto the organization. Maybe you run a\nbusiness and you have an ex account, a\nYouTube account. You want a sub agent to\nmanage those things. You slowly layer on\nanother sub agent, a social media\nmanager. You do this one step at a time.\nI wouldn't add more than two in your\nfirst week. Master those two, get them\nin your workflows, and then you can\nlayer on from there. Let's talk about\ncustomization real quick. I showed you\nsome basic use cases, coding, research.\nWhat it comes down to is you want this\norganization to be custom to you. And\nthe best way to do this, again, if you\nwatch my videos, this is going to be\nlike the 10,000th time you heard this.\nReverse prompting. Reverse prompting is\nwhen instead of you telling what the AI\nto do, you ask it what you can do based\non what you know about me, my goals, my\nworkflows, what would be some good sub\nagents we can spin up and assign. Your\nopen cloud knows way more about you than\nI do. So, it will know based on all your\nconversations which sub agents you\nshould set up. It'll give you a list.\nChoose just one, have it set up, and\nstart using it. This is going to be the\nbest way to set up your own AI\norganization. Feel free to copy me. I\ndon't recommend it because me and you\nare probably different people with\ndifferent workflows, but you can copy me\nto start, but always make sure you\nreverse prompt so you can set up your\nown custom organization. Let's also talk\nabout future state real quick here. What\nI think the future of all of this is,\nand I think the future of all of this is\nlocal AI. Right now, if you have sub\nagents going 24/7, 365, it could get\npricey. It could use up a lot of your\nlimits. That's why I think local AI is\nso important. This is my setup here. I\nhave three Mac Studios, a DJX Spark, and\na Mac Mini. You don't need to do this.\nYou don't need to run out. This is like\n$40,000 computers. You don't need to do\nthat. You can start small with one\ncomputer, one DJX Spark, right? Load a\nmodel onto it and have that model\nhandling one of your sub agents\nactivities. Maybe you load up Quen on\nthere and then Quen 3.5 handles all your\nresearch. Now you've offloaded one\nspecific task to a local model that will\ncost you 0.0 in tokens. Yes, you're\nspending some money upfront for the\ncomputer, but now in perpetuity till the\nend of time, it can do work for you 24/7\nwithout costing you anything. This is\nwhat I believe is the future. Having\nswarms of local agents constantly all\nday and night doing work for you because\nit's going to cost you a little bit of\nmoney up front, but no money after that.\nIf you were to swarm a hundred sub\nagents doing work 24/7, you're probably\npaying thousands and thousands and\nthousands of dollars a year. If you buy\ncomputers, it's just one upfront cost\nand then it cost you nothing after that.\nThis is what I think the future state\nis. I'd recommend thinking about this\nand think about how you can slowly layer\nthis into your workflow. But this is\nwhat I believe the future state is. Hey,\nI'm open to disagreement if you want to\nlet me know that I'm stupid. I don't\ncare. But this is what I think is the\nfuture and this is what I'm investing\nin. I really hope this was helpful. In\nthe next video, I'm going to talk about\nbuilding your own AI research lab, how\nyou can have your sub agents actually\ntraining models for you. It's a little\nadvanced. If you think that's too much,\nlet me know down below. If you want to\nsee that, let me know down below. It's a\nlittle bit outside of what I normally\ndo, so I want to get feedback before I\nfilm it. So, let me know down below. If\nyou have any other questions for me, I'm\nalways in the Vibe Coding Academy. You\ncan post questions in there. There's\nalso a thousand people to answer your\nquestions, too. It's a whole community\nof OpenClaw and Claude Code people. link\nfor that down below. Make sure to join.\nHope this was helpful.\n\n3.0s · 18m 8s YouTube · 4.1k words · text via transcript/captionTracks","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-yoyos"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774922338605}}
{"type":"message","id":"d599e743","parentId":"8eda4a63","timestamp":"2026-03-31T01:58:58.608Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_kmxxlfgalb3b_5","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nI'm about to show you how to give your\nopen claw superpowers. You need to build\na mission control inside your Open Claw.\nAnd in this video, I'll show you how to\ndo it in just a couple of prompts.\nMission control is a custom dashboard\nfor your OpenClaw that allows it to\nbuild any tool it needs on the fly. In\nthis video, I'll take you through my\nentire mission control setup, every tool\nI use, and show you how to set up your\nown in just a couple of prompts. Zero\nprogramming experience needed, zero\ntechnical experience needed. If you\nstick with me until the end, I promise\nyour open claw is going to be a hundred\ntimes more powerful no matter who you\nare. Let's get into it. If you're\nwondering about the different\nbackground, I'm reporting in straight\nfrom Shabuya. I'm going to take you\nthrough every critical mission control\ntool I have. This is my mission control.\nI truly believe everyone, no matter who\nyou are, if you are using Open Claw, you\nneed to be using mission control. This\nmakes it so much better and also just a\nlot more fun to use. This is completely\ncustom. This is a completely custom\ndashboard. All the tools you see on the\nlefth hand side were all built by my\nopen claw. Nothing is out of the box.\nNothing was downloaded from the web. All\ncustom built and I didn't write a single\nline of code. The open claw made all of\nit. So here's what I'm going to do. I'm\ngoing to take you through every mission\ncontrol tool. You need to have your open\nclaw build. These will be relevant to\neveryone. I'm not going to go through\nevery tool on the lefth hand side. Some\nof them are still experimental that I'm\nbuilding out. We'll do follow-up videos\nwith those. But the ones that work that\nare great and everyone should have them,\nI'm about to show you. And these were\nall built simply from me going to my\nopen claw and saying, \"Hey, build me out\na tool in my mission control that does\nthis or build me out a tool in my\nmission control that shows my calendar\nor shows me what tasks I'm working on.\"\nJust one simple prompt and it was all\nbuilt. If you'd like to build this out\nside by side with me as I go through all\nmy tools, feel free to pause right now.\ngo to your OpenClaw and say, \"Hey, I\nwant my own mission control where we can\nbuild custom tools. Please build it in\nNex.js and host it on the local host.\"\nOnce you do that, it will build a\ntemplate. You can also say make it a\nclean interface that looks like linear\nand you'll get a mission control that's\nas beautiful as this. So, let's go into\nit. Let's go into all the critical tools\nyou need in your mission control. As you\ngo, feel free to pause and describe each\ntool and your open claw will do it. So,\nI want to start off on the task board. I\nthink this is a critical critical tool.\nThis taskboard makes it so easy for me\nto track everything my Open Claw is\ndoing. I can see what Henry's working\non. I can see what Henry's sub agents\nare working on. I'm always on top of\nwhat they're doing. This solves a lot of\nproblems. This solves the biggest\nproblem where people go, \"Oh, I don't\nknow what my open claw is doing. I don't\nknow what it completed. I don't know if\nit's halfway done tasks.\" You don't have\nvisibility into what your open claw did.\nNow, with this task board, you know\neverything your open claw is doing and\nwhat it's accomplished. So you can see\nhere it is a simple cananband board\nwhere every task is on here is assigned\nto either me or Henry. You can see the A\nis for me, the H is for Henry. It shows\na description of the task and really\nimportant is over on the left hand side\nis a live activity feed which allows me\nto see every single thing Henry is doing\nin detail. So this just allows me to\nconfirm Henry is doing the work he's\nsaying he's doing. As Henry does the\nwork, he moves the tasks over on the\nboard towards the right until it's done.\nAnything that needs to be reviewed by me\nis right in review and I can go and just\napprove it. Just a great way to manage\nand track everything your open claw\ndoes. If you need to add new tasks, you\ncan hit new task and if you assign it to\nHenry or your openclaw, your open claw\nwill automatically find that and do the\ntask for you. What I did was I asked my\nopenclaw that in every heartbeat check\nour task board, see if any tasks are\nassigned to my openclaw in the backlog\nand then do any tasks that are assigned\nto them. So, every heartbeat is checking\nthis task board to see if any tasks are\nassigned and getting it done\nautonomously. This increased my\nefficiency and also just keeps me on top\nof whatever Henry is doing. Make sure to\nbuild this task board. Just describe\nwhat I showed to you and your agent will\nbuild it for you. No coding at all. The\nnext screen I want to show you is one of\nthe most important ones I'll show you.\nThis is the calendar screen. And the\nreason why this is so powerful is it\nshows you what cron jobs and what tasks\nyou have scheduled for your open claw.\nOne of the biggest complaints I get\nabout OpenClaw is that it's not\nproactive enough. That it's not doing\nproactive tasks for the users. This\nallows you to confirm that your OpenClaw\nis being proactive. Whenever you say,\n\"Hey, do something for me at night. Do\nsomething for me every morning. Do\nsomething productive every afternoon.\"\nYou can come to your calendar screen and\nsee and confirm that your open claw\nscheduled those cron jobs to do those\ntasks. There's an issue I've been seeing\nwith people. Some open clauses, they\nsay, \"Hey, I'll do that for you.\" and\nthen they never actually do those\nthings. This calendar is a great way to\nconfirm it. And this also puts you and\nyour 