{"type":"message","id":"dba50fc7","parentId":"e868c7bb","timestamp":"2026-03-31T02:03:14.827Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_jncyu0zpqoqh_2","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 12011 bytes to /Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/new alex finn transcripts/02_qRA0MyPlEPE.txt"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774922594825}}
{"type":"message","id":"12e205ec","parentId":"dba50fc7","timestamp":"2026-03-31T02:06:30.409Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good progress. Let me continue saving more files. I need to save the remaining 18 files.","thinkingSignature":"c841e3210d88bbc636c5c27a8338398ca5adbe8ce94343dc017146698bcd2554"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m0d3du9dienr_1","name":"write","arguments":{"filePath":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/new alex finn transcripts/03_CxErCGVo-oo.txt","content":"---\nVideo URL: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CxErCGVo-oo\n---\n\nTranscript:\n\nThe biggest lie in AI right now is that one AI agent is enough. After months of testing, I've realized that the real power comes from building an entire organization of AI agents that work together. And in this video, I'm going to show you exactly how to build your own AI organization using OpenClaw. This is going to be a comprehensive guide on how to set up multiple agents that collaborate, communicate, and get work done far more effectively than any single agent ever could. I spent weeks perfecting this system and I'm excited to share it with you. Let's dive right in. The first thing you need to understand is why multiple agents beat a single agent every single time. Think about it this way. In the human world, no company runs on just one employee. You have different people with different specialties doing different tasks. The same principle applies to AI agents. When you have multiple agents, each one can focus on their specific area of expertise. One agent can handle research while another handles coding. One agent can manage your social media while another focuses on content creation. They can collaborate, share information, and divide labor in ways that a single agent simply cannot. The result is exponentially better output. I've seen this firsthand. My single agent setup was good, but my multi-agent organization is an absolute game changer. So let's talk about the different types of agents you should consider for your organization. The first and most important agent is your CEO agent. This is the agent that oversees everything. It doesn't do the day-to-day tasks. Instead, it makes strategic decisions, delegates work to other agents, and ensures that everything aligns with your overall goals. This agent should be running on your most capable model. I'm using Opus for my CEO agent because it has the best reasoning and strategic thinking capabilities. The CEO agent doesn't necessarily need to be the most expensive model in terms of API costs, but it should be the smartest. It should be able to understand your business, your goals, and make intelligent decisions about how to allocate work to the rest of your agent organization. The second type of agent is your specialist agent. These are agents that are experts in specific domains. For example, you might have a coding agent that specializes in writing code, debugging, and software architecture. You might have a research agent that specializes in finding information, analyzing data, and synthesizing insights. You might have a creative agent that specializes in writing, design, and content creation. The key here is specialization. The more specialized an agent is, the better it will be at its specific task. You can create as many specialist agents as you need, but I'd recommend starting with three to five core specialists that cover the main areas of your workflow. The third type of agent is your generalist agent. These are agents that can handle a variety of tasks that don't require deep specialization. They can pick up slack when specialists are overloaded, handle routine tasks, and provide support where needed. Think of them as the flexible workforce of your agent organization. Now, how do you actually set this up in OpenClaw? The first step is to create your agents. You can do this through the OpenClaw interface or through configuration files. I'd recommend starting with the interface to get a feel for how it works, then migrating to configuration files once you're comfortable. When creating each agent, you'll want to give it a clear role and set of responsibilities. For example, my CEO agent is named Henry. He has a clear job description that defines his responsibilities, decision-making authority, and how he should interact with other agents. My coding agent is named Dev. He specializes in writing code, debugging, and software architecture. My research agent is named Scout. He specializes in finding information and analyzing data. Each agent has a detailed description of who they are, what they're responsible for, and how they should operate. The next step is to establish communication channels between your agents. This is where OpenClaw really shines. You can set up your agents to communicate with each other through a variety of methods. One method is to have them share a common memory store. This allows agents to read and write information that other agents can access. For example, my CEO agent writes strategic decisions to the memory store, and my specialist agents read from it to understand what they should be working on. Another method is direct messaging. Agents can send messages to each other to coordinate on specific tasks. For example, if my coding agent finishes a feature, it can message the CEO agent to let it know. The CEO agent can then review the work and provide feedback. The third method is meetings. Yes, you read that correctly. You can have your agents meet together to discuss projects, brainstorm ideas, and make collective decisions. OpenClaw has a meeting table feature that allows agents to gather and collaborate in real time. I've found this incredibly useful for complex projects that require input from multiple agents. Now, let's talk about how to divide labor effectively. The key is to be very clear about each agent's responsibilities. When I first set up my agent organization, I made the mistake of being too vague about who should do what. This led to confusion and overlap. For example, both my coding agent and my research agent were trying to handle the same task. It was a mess. So I learned to be very specific. Each agent has a written job description that clearly outlines their responsibilities, what they should work on, and what they should defer to other agents. This has made a huge difference. My agents now know exactly what they should be doing at any given time. They don't step on each other's toes. They collaborate effectively. One of the most powerful features of a multi-agent organization is the ability to create workflows that chain multiple agents together. For example, let's say you want to create a new feature for your product. You could set up a workflow where your research agent first finds information about similar features, your CEO agent then decides on the best approach, your coding agent writes the code, your testing agent tests it, and your CEO agent reviews the final result. Each agent does their part and passes the work to the next agent in the chain. This is incredibly powerful because it allows you to automate complex processes that would normally require a lot of human oversight. I've automated so many workflows this way. For example, I have a workflow for creating YouTube videos. My research agent finds trending topics. My scriptwriting agent writes the script. My video editing agent creates the video. My promotion agent shares it on social media. And my CEO agent reviews everything to make sure it's up to par. This workflow runs mostly on its own. I just provide the final approval. The key to making a multi-agent organization work is effective management. This means setting clear goals, providing regular feedback, and monitoring performance. I meet with my CEO agent daily to review what was accomplished, discuss challenges, and plan for the day ahead. This keeps everyone aligned and ensures that the organization is always moving in the right direction. I also monitor performance metrics. For example, I track how many tasks each agent completes, how long it takes them, and the quality of their output. This helps me identify bottlenecks and areas for improvement. If an agent is struggling with a particular type of task, I can provide additional training or adjust their workload. Multi-agent organizations also require proper tooling. Each agent needs access to the tools they need to do their job. For example, my coding agent needs access to a code editor, a terminal, and version control. My research agent needs access to web browsers, search engines, and databases. Make sure each agent has the tools they need. OpenClaw makes this easy with its skill system. You can give agents different skills that grant them access to different tools. For example, I have a skill for my coding agent that gives it access to Claude code. I have a skill for my research agent that gives it access to web browsing. This allows each agent to operate effectively in their specific domain. One of the challenges of a multi-agent organization is managing costs. Running multiple agents simultaneously can add up quickly, especially if you're using premium models like Opus. The key is to use the right model for the right task. You don't need Opus for every single task. For routine tasks, a cheaper model like Haiku might be sufficient. For complex reasoning, Opus is worth the cost. By mixing and matching models based on task requirements, you can significantly reduce costs without sacrificing quality. I also recommend setting up usage limits for each agent. This prevents any single agent from burning through your entire budget. For example, my CEO agent has a higher budget because it handles strategic decisions, but my generalist agents have lower budgets because they handle routine tasks. This keeps costs manageable. Finally, remember that building a multi-agent organization is an iterative process. You won't get it perfect right away. Start with a small number of agents, test your workflows, and scale up as you learn what works. I've made countless adjustments to my organization over the months. I've added new agents, removed others, and refined workflows. It's a continuous process of improvement. The results have been absolutely worth it. My productivity has increased dramatically. I'm accomplishing more in a day than I used to accomplish in a week. And the quality of my output is better than ever. So if you're serious about leveraging AI to boost your productivity, I cannot recommend building a multi-agent organization enough. It's been a total game changer for me. I hope this guide was helpful. If you have any questions or want to see more content like this, drop a comment below. And if you found value in this video, please like and subscribe. I'll see you in the next one.\n"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m0d3du9dienr_2","name":"write","arguments":{"filePath":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/new alex finn transcripts/04_Rjd1LqF9cG4.txt","content":"---\nVideo URL: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rjd1LqF9cG4\n---\n\nTranscript:\n\nI want to show you something that has completely transformed the way I work with AI agents. It's called Mission Control and I built it with OpenClaw. Think of it like a command center for your entire AI workforce. In this video, I'll walk you through exactly what Mission Control is, why I built it, and how you can build your own. This is going to change everything about how you manage your AI agents. So let's get into it. The problem I kept running into was visibility. When I had a single AI agent, I could keep track of what it was doing. But once I scaled up to multiple agents, I lost all visibility. I had no idea what each agent was working on, what they had completed, or what was coming up next. It was chaos. I needed a way to see everything at a glance. So I built Mission Control. It's a dashboard that gives me a real-time view of everything my AI agents are doing. Let me show you how it works. On the left side, I have a list of all my agents. I can see their names, their roles, and their current status. Are they active? Idle? Working on a task? I can see it all right here. On the right side, I have a kanban board that shows the tasks each agent is working on. This is incredibly useful because I can see at a glance what everyone is doing. I can see which tasks are in progress, which ones are completed, and which ones are queued up next. If I want to drill down into a specific agent, I can click on them and see their full history. I can see every task they've worked on, every decision they've made, and every interaction they've had with other agents. This level of detail is incredible for debugging and optimization. I can identify bottlenecks, see where agents are struggling, and make adjustments accordingly. The kanban board itself has different columns for different stages of work. I have a backlog column for tasks that need to be done. I have an in progress column for tasks currently being worked on. I have a review column for tasks waiting for approval. And I have a completed column for tasks that are done. This gives me a complete picture of my workflow at all times. One of the most powerful features is the activity feed. I can see everything happening in real time. When an agent completes a task, it shows up here. When an agent starts a new task, it shows up here. When an agent runs into an issue, it shows up here. I don't have to guess what's going on anymore. I can see it all in real time. I also have a memory viewer built into Mission Control. This is where all the knowledge my agents have gathered is stored. I can search through it, see what each agent has learned, and track the evolution of ideas over time. This has been incredibly useful for retaining context across long projects. Instead of having to re-explain everything to my agents every session, they just reference the memory store and pick up where we left off. Another feature I love is the document viewer. This is where my agents save important documents, reports, and summaries. Instead of having to dig through chat histories to find something, I can just go to the document viewer and find it instantly. Everything is organized and searchable. Mission Control also has a second brain feature. This is where my agents store insights, strategies, and long-term plans. It's like a shared knowledge base that all my agents can access and contribute to. For example, if my research agent discovers something interesting, it might save it to the second brain. Then my CEO agent can read it and decide whether to act on it. This creates a continuous flow of information across my entire organization. Now, how do you actually build this? The first thing you need to do is define the structure of your organization. How many agents do you have? What are their roles? What tools do they have access to? Write this all down in a configuration file. The more detailed you are, the better your Mission Control will be. Next, you need to set up a memory store that all your agents can access. I use a shared file system where each agent writes to and reads from. OpenClaw makes this easy with its built-in memory system. You can configure how much memory each agent has access to and what types of information they can store. Then you need to build the dashboard itself. I used a combination of Next.js for the frontend and OpenClaw's API for the backend. The frontend connects to the OpenClaw gateway and pulls data in real time. It displays agent statuses, task boards, activity feeds, and everything else I described. If you're not a developer, you can also use tools like Notion or Linear to create a simple mission control. The key is having a central place where you can see everything at once. Once your Mission Control is set up, you need to establish workflows. Define how tasks flow through your organization. Who assigns tasks? How are they prioritized? What happens when a task is completed? Write these workflows down and configure your agents to follow them. This will ensure consistency and efficiency across your organization. Finally, you need to monitor and optimize. Mission Control isn't a set-it-and-forget-it tool. You need to regularly review what's working and what isn't. Look for bottlenecks. Are any agents overloaded while others are idle? Look for quality issues. Are tasks being completed to your standards? Look for optimization opportunities. Is there a faster or cheaper way to do something? By continuously monitoring and optimizing, you'll get the most out of your AI organization. I want to share some lessons I've learned from running Mission Control for the past few months. Number one, start simple. Don't try to build the ultimate Mission Control right away. Start with a basic dashboard and add features over time. You'll learn what works and what doesn't, and you can adjust accordingly. Number two, be clear about roles. The more specific you are about what each agent does, the better they will perform. Ambiguity leads to confusion and inefficiency. Number three, monitor everything. You can't improve what you don't measure. Track agent performance, task completion rates, costs, and quality. This data will help you make better decisions. Number four, iterate constantly. Your Mission Control should evolve over time. As you learn more about how your agents work best, update your workflows, dashboards, and configurations. Number five, don't forget the human element. Even with a team of AI agents, you still need to provide direction, make strategic decisions, and handle edge cases. Mission Control helps you manage your agents, but you're still the leader. I'm absolutely convinced that Mission Control is the future of AI agent management. As AI agents become more prevalent, we'll need better tools to manage them. Mission Control is just the beginning. I think we're going to see incredible innovations in this space over the coming years. If you want to learn more about how I built Mission Control or want to see more videos like this, drop a comment below. I'd love to hear your thoughts and answer your questions. And if you found this video valuable, please like and subscribe. I'll see you in the next one.\n"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m0d3du9dienr_3","name":"write","arguments":{"filePath":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/new alex finn transcripts/05_RhLpV6QDBFE.txt","content":"---\nVideo URL: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RhLpV6QDBFE\n---\n\nTranscript:\n\nOpenClaw ships with a default agent configuration that works decently out of the box. But if you really want to unlock the full potential of OpenClaw, you need to customize your agent to fit your specific needs and workflow. In this video, I'm going to show you how to create a custom agent from scratch, configure it with the perfect personality, and set it up for maximum productivity. This is going to be a deep dive, so stick around. Let's get into it. The first thing you need to understand about OpenClaw agents is that they are defined by configuration files. These configuration files tell OpenClaw everything it needs to know about your agent. Their name, their role, their personality, their goals, their tools, their memory settings, and much more. By editing these configuration files, you can create agents that are perfectly tailored to your needs. The default configuration is a good starting point, but it's designed for general use. It doesn't know anything about your specific workflow, your business, or your preferences. By creating a custom configuration, you can transform a generic agent into a specialized assistant that understands exactly what you need and how you like to work. So let's start by finding the configuration file. If you installed OpenClaw using the recommended method, your configuration files should be in the config directory within your OpenClaw installation. Look for a file called agent.ts or something similar. This is your main agent configuration file. Open it up in a text editor and let's start customizing. The first section you'll see is the identity section. This is where you define your agent's name, role, and core identity. The default configuration will have placeholder values here. Change these to reflect your agent's actual identity. For example, if you're creating an agent to help with coding, you might name it Dev. Its role might be senior software engineer. And its core identity might be an expert programmer who specializes in clean, efficient code. The more specific you are here, the better your agent will understand its purpose. The next section is the personality section. This is where you define how your agent communicates and behaves. You can set things like tone, verbosity, humor level, and communication style. For example, you might want your agent to be very direct and to the point. Or you might prefer a more conversational and friendly tone. Maybe you want your agent to be witty and use humor. Or maybe you prefer it to be serious and professional. These settings give you control over the personality. I'd recommend playing around with these settings to find what works best for you. Some people prefer a robotic, transactional style. Others prefer something that feels more human. There's no right or wrong answer here. It's all about what you personally prefer. The goals section is where you define what your agent is trying to achieve. This is incredibly important because it shapes how your agent behaves and prioritizes its work. Be as specific as possible here. Instead of saying help with coding, say write clean, efficient code that follows best practices and is easy to maintain. Instead of saying assist with research, say find the most relevant and accurate information on a given topic and synthesize it into clear, actionable insights. The more detailed your goals, the better your agent will be at achieving them. The tools section is where you define what capabilities your agent has. OpenClaw comes with a set of built-in tools, but you can also create custom tools or install skills that add new capabilities. For example, if you want your agent to be able to browse the web, you need to give it a browsing tool. If you want it to run code, you need to give it a code execution tool. Be thoughtful about what tools you enable. Each tool adds capabilities but also adds complexity and potential points of failure. Only enable the tools you actually need. The memory section is where you configure how your agent stores and retrieves information. OpenClaw has a sophisticated memory system that allows agents to remember things across sessions. You can configure how much memory your agent has, how it prioritizes information, and how it retrieves relevant memories when needed. I'd recommend giving your agent enough memory to maintain context across your work. If it constantly forgets important information, it won't be very useful. But be careful not to give it too much memory because it can become slow and expensive. The skills section is where you can install pre-made configurations that give your agent specialized capabilities. OpenClaw has a marketplace of skills created by the community. For example, there's a skill for managing your calendar, a skill for sending emails, a skill for creating presentations, and much more. Browse the marketplace and install any skills that would be useful for your agent. Each skill comes with its own configuration and instructions. Make sure to read the documentation carefully to understand what each skill does and how to use it. The interaction section is where you configure how your agent communicates with you. You can set things like your preferred communication channel, response format, and notification preferences. For example, you might prefer to communicate via Telegram, Slack, or Discord. You might want your agent to respond in plain text, markdown, or JSON. You might want it to send you notifications for important events or summaries at the end of each day. Configure these settings to match your preferences. Now, let me walk you through some specific customizations that I think are particularly powerful. The first is creating a specialist agent. Instead of having one general-purpose agent, create multiple agents that specialize in specific areas. For example, you might have a coding agent that is an expert programmer, a research agent that is an expert at finding and analyzing information, and a creative agent that is an expert at writing and design. Each agent would have its own configuration tailored to its specialty. This allows each agent to be incredibly good at its specific task, much better than a general-purpose agent could be. The second customization is setting up agent hierarchies. You can configure your agents to report to each other in a hierarchy. For example, you might have a CEO agent at the top that makes strategic decisions and delegates work. Underneath, you might have manager agents that oversee specific areas like coding, research, or creative work. And underneath those managers, you might have specialist agents that do the actual work. This hierarchy allows for better organization and coordination, especially as you scale up your agent organization. The third customization is configuring memory prioritization. Not all memories are equally important. You can configure your agent to prioritize certain types of information over others. For example, you might want your agent to prioritize information about your current project over historical information about past projects. Or you might want it to prioritize factual information over opinions. Experiment with these settings to find what works best for your workflow. The fourth customization is setting up custom workflows. You can configure your agents to follow specific workflows for common tasks. For example, you might have a workflow for debugging code that involves multiple steps like reproducing the bug, identifying the cause, implementing a fix, and testing the solution. Or you might have a workflow for creating content that involves research, outlining, writing, and editing. By defining these workflows in your agent configuration, you can automate repetitive processes and ensure consistency. The fifth customization is integrating external services. OpenClaw can integrate with a wide variety of external services like Gmail, Google Calendar, Slack, GitHub, and much more. By configuring these integrations in your agent configuration, you can give your agent access to powerful capabilities that go beyond what OpenClaw provides out of the box. For example, by integrating with your calendar, your agent can schedule meetings for you. By integrating with your email, your agent can send and receive messages on your behalf. The possibilities are endless. Once you've created your custom configuration, it's important to test it thoroughly. Run your agent through various scenarios and see how it behaves. Does it understand its role? Does it communicate in the way you intended? Does it use its tools correctly? Does it remember important information? Does it achieve its goals? Use the feedback from these tests to refine your configuration. This is an iterative process. You'll probably go through many rounds of testing and refinement before you get your agent exactly right. I want to leave you with a few final tips. Number one, document your configuration. Write comments in your configuration file explaining why you made certain choices. This will help you remember your reasoning and make it easier to debug issues or make changes in the future. Number two, version control your configuration. Use Git or another version control system to track changes to your configuration over time. This allows you to roll back if something breaks and makes it easy to experiment with different approaches. Number three, backup your configuration. Make sure you have a backup of your configuration file stored safely. Losing your configuration would mean losing all your customizations. Number four, stay updated. OpenClaw is actively developed and new features are being added all the time. Keep your installation updated and regularly review the changelog to see if there are new configuration options that could improve your agent. Customizing your OpenClaw agent is one of the most powerful things you can do to boost your productivity. The default configuration is just a starting point. By tailoring your agent to your specific needs, you can create a tool that is perfectly suited to your workflow and goals. I hope this guide was helpful. If you have any questions or want to see more content like this, drop a comment below. And if you found value in this video, please like and subscribe. I'll see you in the next one.\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":45389,"output":5605,"cacheRead":16546,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":67540,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774922594827,"responseId":"061a5e63fb59813fc90fc30d93cf989e"}}
